{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1781682991,"nonce":"nCrDqu3fyTvbUNQq1njnS+teB1w=","title":"Predicate vocabulary: LIKE/ILIKE, IN/NOT IN, BETWEEN, bool-column-as-predicate","message":"expr.rs exposes only comparisons (equals/not_equals/less_than(_or_equals)/greater_than(_or_equals)), is_null/is_not_null, and/or/not_, and arithmetic (add/subtract/multiply/divide). The everyday predicate operators are missing:\n\n- LIKE / ILIKE (pattern matching), with a literal or param pattern operand.\n- IN (...) / NOT IN (...) over a value list (and later a subquery, see the subquery bug).\n- BETWEEN lo AND hi.\n- Using a bool column directly as a predicate (today a bool column cannot be dropped into where_ without an equals(true)).\n\nNote: `crates/squealy-postgresql/src/canonical.rs` already parses like/ilike/between/in/coalesce for index-predicate diffing, so the SQL semantics are partly modelled already — this is about surfacing them as typed builder methods in `crates/squealy/src/expr.rs` and rendering them in each backend.\n\nOperand typing should reuse the existing comparison machinery so a wrong-typed RHS is a compile error.","files":null}]}